How it’s going vs how it started🌼

21 months of exclusive breastfeeding. 21 months of learning, nurturing, sacrificing, sleeping, pumping, loving, working, not sleeping, and nursing my boy. We’re coming to the end…and I have a lot of emotions about it. Each day I’m so humbled watching this human grow and knowing I’m his fuel. Soon he’ll be weaned and I’ll treasure our precious moments before bed where we talk, snuggle, nurse+reflect on his day. Mamas whether it’s for 7 days, 4 months, 10 months or 2 years…breastfeed where YOU, how YOU want, and when YOUR baby needs it. I’m rooting for you💕images by the talented @weepphoto

My baby boy is 2🎈where has time gone? My life has changed, priorities are different now. I model less and mom more, a thought that used to scare me. Not anymore. Women are amazing: black women take my breath away🫶🏾Each Black mother carries with her the remnants of breastfeeding trauma that has traveled through generations into the experience of birthing+nursing today. While many Black women look to their elders+veterans in parenting for breastfeeding advice, this advice is less often empowering or beneficial when for generations it wasn’t experienced or viewed in a positive way. Historically, breastfeeding was seen as self-demeaning and women who were seen breastfeeding were seen as uncultured, poor, and often shunned. This, in large part, is why white mothers exploited Black mothers’ milk. The joys of pregnancy quickly faded away for enslaved Black women who were used as “wet-nurses” often pulled from their families, friends, and babies…forced to breastfeed children of their salve holders. 

24 months of exclusive breastfeeding has come to an end✊🏾every latch, every snuggle, every tear, every smile, and every yawn was done so willfully. Not solely for the nourishment of my baby, but for every wound of every woman before me who wasn’t able to do so herself. Beyoncé said it best. I’m “thankful for the beauty that comes with a painful history, and I rejoice in the pain, rejoice in the imperfections, and the wrongs that are so damn right.” 

If you read this I hope you feel 1/100 of the joy that I feel when I’m nursing my baby boy. Mamas, whether it’s for 2 weeks, 4 months, 11 months, or 2yrs…nurse your baby when YOU want, where YOU want, and when YOUR baby needs it. I’m rooting for you💞 #blackbreastfeedingweek #blackmotherhood #breastfeeding #mother #motherhood #love
